02:24.344 --> 02:26.412
     Afternoon, everybody.      

02:26.479 --> 02:28.147
                            ALL:
                        Norm!   

02:28.214 --> 02:29.782
          Oh, hey, Mr. Peterson,
         that's quite a haircut.

02:29.849 --> 02:32.084
    Yeah, well, they're only    
      halfway done, Woody.      

02:34.487 --> 02:35.821
    I got a little thirsty.     

02:35.889 --> 02:37.823
     You know what I mean?      

02:37.891 --> 02:39.591
        Give me a beer.         

02:40.927 --> 02:42.961
        Hi, Woody.              

02:43.029 --> 02:44.830
        Oh, hey, Kelly.         
    What are you doing here?    

02:44.898 --> 02:46.331
                     I wanted to
             spend the afternoon

02:46.466 --> 02:48.133
    with Mr. Peterson           
        and Mr. Clavin.         

02:48.201 --> 02:49.935
Boy, you've been spending       
         a lot of time          

02:50.003 --> 02:51.103
  with them lately. What's up?  

02:51.171 --> 02:52.404
              I thought it would
                  be a good idea

02:52.472 --> 02:53.672
                for me to get to
              know your friends.

02:53.740 --> 02:54.873
Why?                            

02:54.941 --> 02:56.108
                    Because when
                 we get married,

02:56.176 --> 02:58.177
              and you turn to me
                and say, "Kelly,

02:58.244 --> 02:59.878
            I'm gonna spend a   
             night on the town,"

02:59.946 --> 03:01.547
                and I burst into
            tears and ask you   

03:01.614 --> 03:03.248
            to spend just one   
              night at home, and

03:03.316 --> 03:05.317
             you say, "I'm gonna
            be with my friends,"

03:05.385 --> 03:08.787
            well, I want to know
          who those friends are.

03:08.855 --> 03:12.458
Boy, could I sing               
a couple bars of that.          

03:12.525 --> 03:14.460
So, what do you guys            
talk about?                     

03:14.527 --> 03:15.894
                  Oh, the usual.

03:15.962 --> 03:18.097
                 How the Celtics
             need a point guard,

03:18.164 --> 03:19.732
          the Sox need pitching,

03:19.799 --> 03:22.201
        the fact that there's an
      exact replica of the earth

03:22.268 --> 03:25.170
        on the other side of the
      sun that we can never see.

03:25.238 --> 03:26.939
Wow. Really?                    

03:27.007 --> 03:28.474
The Sox need pitchers?          

03:28.541 --> 03:30.843
            Well, on this earth.

03:30.910 --> 03:32.277
            Anyway, Woody, if   
        you'll excuse me now,   

03:32.345 --> 03:34.546
    one of your friends is gonna
      teach me how to play pool.

03:34.614 --> 03:35.814
Oh, which one?                  

03:35.882 --> 03:37.316
                I don't remember
                his name, but   

03:37.384 --> 03:40.786
    he's the man from the CIA   
    who trains the Green Berets.

03:40.854 --> 03:42.821
  Let's go, tootsie. We're up.  

03:45.959 --> 03:47.893
         Do you realize         
    it's been 18 years          

03:47.994 --> 03:49.928
  since we've seen each other?  

03:49.996 --> 03:51.964
     Me, too. I can't wait.     

03:52.032 --> 03:53.232
         Okay. Bye-bye.         

03:53.299 --> 03:55.534
              You'll never guess
                who that was.   

03:55.602 --> 03:58.904
Your dental hygienist?          

03:58.972 --> 04:02.441
                     Come on. Be
                 serious. Guess.

04:02.509 --> 04:04.376
Okay, I'll be serious.          

04:04.444 --> 04:05.577
I don't really care.            

04:05.645 --> 04:06.979
                        (scoffs)

04:07.047 --> 04:08.547
Well, I'm gonna tell you anyway.

04:08.615 --> 04:09.748
     It was Mark Newberger.     

04:09.816 --> 04:12.251
We have not seen each other     
since graduation night.         

04:12.318 --> 04:14.153
Oh, Mark Newberger.             

04:14.220 --> 04:17.089
We met doing <i>The Bad Seed</i>       
  in our sophomore production.  

04:17.156 --> 04:19.358
He was my first boyfriend.      

04:19.426 --> 04:21.694
      I really loved him.       

04:21.761 --> 04:24.063
Maybe he was the <i>only</i> guy       
I've ever really loved.         

04:24.130 --> 04:25.998
I don't know                    
why I gave him up.              

04:26.066 --> 04:29.134
Oh, I guess I wanted to go off  
to college and be free,         

04:29.202 --> 04:30.269
        that whole deal.        

04:30.337 --> 04:31.370
                I don't know.   
                  What an idiot.

04:31.438 --> 04:33.372
                Why would I ever
                    give him up?

04:33.440 --> 04:36.408
Nobody's listening              
to you.                         

04:36.476 --> 04:39.945
     I am trying to pretend     
  like I have a friend, okay?   

04:40.013 --> 04:41.246
         Wait. What am I saying?

04:41.314 --> 04:43.482
        I do have a friend. I   
          don't need to pretend.

04:43.550 --> 04:44.717
         Mark Newberger is back,

04:44.784 --> 04:46.552
            and he's better than
            any friend <i>you</i> have!

04:46.619 --> 04:47.753
I'm sorry.                      

04:47.821 --> 04:49.388
I wasn't listening.             

04:51.624 --> 04:53.726
                 Anybody in here
                  know this guy?

04:53.793 --> 04:56.095
Sam! My God, what's the matter? 

04:56.162 --> 04:57.663
        We found him out        
  in the middle of the street   

04:57.731 --> 04:58.964
      staring at an empty       
         parking space,         

04:59.032 --> 05:01.200
     muttering to himself,      
      shouting at people.       

05:01.267 --> 05:02.568
SAM:                            
My corvette!                    

05:02.635 --> 05:04.470
They stole my 'Vette!           

05:04.537 --> 05:06.438
Frasier, have you seen          
my 'Vette?                      

05:06.506 --> 05:09.241
                    Oh, Sam, I'm
                     afraid not.

05:09.309 --> 05:11.543
Well, Sam, stop by              
the station house sometime      

05:11.611 --> 05:13.112
and fill out                    
a report.                       

05:13.179 --> 05:14.713
Then you'll give me             
my 'Vette back!                 

05:14.781 --> 05:16.148
Whatever you say.               

05:16.316 --> 05:18.150
            Oh, God.            

05:18.218 --> 05:19.451
I left it outside!              

05:19.519 --> 05:20.753
What was I thinking?            

05:20.820 --> 05:22.488
I should have                   
stayed with it!                 

05:22.555 --> 05:24.356
Boy, oh, boy,                   
oh, boy, Normie,                

05:24.424 --> 05:26.492
I'm gonna miss that car.        

05:26.559 --> 05:28.260
Here, take a look at that.      

05:28.328 --> 05:31.397
            Wow. That's you next
              to Sammy's 'Vette.

05:31.464 --> 05:32.765
    Yeah.                       

05:32.832 --> 05:36.735
Truth be told, I, uh...         
I tell the ladies it's mine.    

05:36.803 --> 05:38.037
Yeah.                           

05:38.104 --> 05:40.673
                Wait. That's not
                 even your body.

05:40.740 --> 05:45.444
          It's Sammy's body with
         your head superimposed.

05:45.512 --> 05:48.447
Yeah, you'd be surprised        
what Ma can do in a darkroom.   

05:48.515 --> 05:52.151
Yeah. Yeah, we got one of, uh,  
me at the Yalta conference.     

05:52.218 --> 05:54.219
    Yeah.                       

05:54.287 --> 05:57.656
You-You should see the look     
that Churchill's giving me.     

05:57.724 --> 06:01.126
          Oh. Oh. Oh!           

06:01.194 --> 06:04.530
    I suppose one of us ought to
     go over and cheer Sammy up.

06:04.597 --> 06:05.698
Uh, yeah, yeah.                 

06:05.765 --> 06:07.266
Well, I'll do it.               
I, uh...                        

06:07.334 --> 06:09.368
I got a flair                   
for this kind of thing.         

06:09.436 --> 06:11.470
You just, uh, stay there        
and drink your beer.            

06:11.538 --> 06:14.540
Okay. We all have to play       
to our strengths, I guess.      

06:14.607 --> 06:15.674
                 Oh, Sammy.     

06:15.742 --> 06:17.543
              Sammy, Sam, Sammy.

06:17.610 --> 06:19.978
        Gee, you know, I, uh,   
    heard about the bad news.   

06:20.046 --> 06:21.180
          I'm really sorry, pal.

06:21.247 --> 06:22.581
              It's, uh, terrible
             what these guys do.

06:22.649 --> 06:24.683
             You know, they, uh,
             just pluck your car

06:24.751 --> 06:26.652
                right up off the
              street and take it

06:26.720 --> 06:28.821
         to what's, uh, commonly
        known as a chop shop.   

06:28.888 --> 06:30.456
                Yeah, where they

06:30.523 --> 06:32.658
 unceremoniously dismantle it,  
        and after that,         

06:32.726 --> 06:35.361
        the felons take         
  an acetylene torch, and, uh,  

06:35.428 --> 06:37.363
            just methodically   
                cut the frame   

06:37.430 --> 06:40.499
                    into little,
                    tiny pieces.

06:40.567 --> 06:42.901
Cliff, do you really think      
    any of this helps?          

06:42.969 --> 06:45.371
  Well, it sure as heck keeps   
the car from being traced, Sam. 

06:48.842 --> 06:51.076
         (raspy voice):         
            Uh, hi.             

06:51.144 --> 06:52.244
I'm looking                     
for Rebecca Howe.               

06:52.312 --> 06:53.479
            She's over there.   

06:54.514 --> 06:56.782
                  Rebecca?      

06:56.850 --> 06:58.851
        My God, Rebecca,        
    you're beautiful!           

06:58.918 --> 07:01.220
Who'd have ever thought         

07:01.287 --> 07:03.355
  that you would've developed   
 into this gorgeous creature?!  

07:03.423 --> 07:05.391
No, Mark!                       
Over here!                      

07:05.458 --> 07:08.193
            Rebecca, you haven't
                  changed a bit!

07:09.262 --> 07:11.163
                    My God, look
                at that hair!   

07:11.231 --> 07:12.731
            If you had any more,

07:12.799 --> 07:14.900
          I could get you listed
    as an endangered species!   

07:14.968 --> 07:16.735
             Well, come on, turn
            around, turn around.

07:16.803 --> 07:18.303
                     Let me see.
                     Let me see.

07:18.371 --> 07:20.406
                  Oh, I like it.
                More to love.   

07:20.473 --> 07:22.041
Me? What about you?!            

07:22.108 --> 07:23.876
             Hey, I'm bulking up
            for the Olympics.   

07:23.943 --> 07:25.844
        (laughs)                
                    You'll never
                     guess what.

07:25.912 --> 07:27.413
      I finally gave up smoking.

07:27.480 --> 07:29.848
Oh, I can tell. Your voice      
sounds so much better.          

07:29.916 --> 07:31.183
Sam?                            

07:31.251 --> 07:32.951
        Sam, I want you         
    to meet somebody.           

07:33.019 --> 07:34.219
  Sam, this is Mark Newberger.  

07:34.287 --> 07:35.721
        Mark Newberger,         
      this is Sam Malone.       

07:35.789 --> 07:36.889
    Sam owns the bar.           

07:36.956 --> 07:39.258
Let me go get some of           
my other friends.               
                        Okay.   

07:39.325 --> 07:41.593
      Hey, guys, guys, I want to
      introduce you to somebody!

07:41.661 --> 07:43.996
Somebody stole my car.          

07:44.064 --> 07:45.931
            Oh, I've been there.

07:45.999 --> 07:47.599
Yeah? Really?                   

07:47.667 --> 07:49.101
              Yeah, my ex-lover.

07:49.169 --> 07:52.471
        First he stole my heart,
        then he stole my car.   

07:52.539 --> 07:55.607
            He?                 

07:55.675 --> 07:58.510
Aren't you supposed             
to be Rebecca's old flame?      

07:58.578 --> 08:00.612
                    Well, I'm   
                not that old.   

08:02.282 --> 08:04.316
             Thank God he didn't
            steal the water bed,

08:04.384 --> 08:07.152
         the lying little tramp.

08:07.220 --> 08:09.355
                        Meow!   

08:09.422 --> 08:11.357
      Like you were there.      

08:13.893 --> 08:15.828
                        REBECCA:
                        Mark,   

08:15.895 --> 08:17.596
        I want you              
    to meet all my friends.     

08:17.664 --> 08:19.498
        All right,              
this is Dr. Sternin-Crane,      

08:19.566 --> 08:20.899
                    our resident
                     researcher.

08:20.967 --> 08:22.067
        This is Cliff Clavin,   

08:22.135 --> 08:24.737
our resident                    
trivia expert.                  

08:24.804 --> 08:25.838
                    This is Norm
                    Peterson,   

08:25.905 --> 08:28.941
our... resident.                

08:29.009 --> 08:31.810
              Uh, this is Woody,
                the bartender   

08:31.878 --> 08:33.178
and Carla,                      
the waitress.                   

08:33.246 --> 08:35.246
                 And what do you
                    do, Rebecca?
(whispering):                   
Shut up!                        

08:35.315 --> 08:37.850
        Thought I could trick   
            her into telling us.

08:39.885 --> 08:41.820
Oh, Lilith,                     
I feel so victimized.           

08:41.888 --> 08:43.822
I feel so angry.                

08:43.890 --> 08:45.391
I don't know what to do.        

08:45.458 --> 08:47.493
            Well, actually, Sam,
        this is precisely how   

08:47.560 --> 08:49.495
                  victim support
             groups got started.

08:49.562 --> 08:51.864
    People who were suffering   
        and unable to cope found

08:51.931 --> 08:53.165
                they felt better

08:53.233 --> 08:55.267
            if they were able to
        share those feelings.   

08:55.335 --> 08:57.803
Well, maybe I should try        
to get in one of those groups.  

08:57.871 --> 08:59.505
I wonder if they have           
a group for people              

08:59.572 --> 09:02.441
who have had high-performance   
automobiles stolen.             

09:02.509 --> 09:03.909
                    You had a   
                     car stolen?
Yeah.                           

09:04.077 --> 09:05.210
            What kind was it?   

09:05.278 --> 09:07.680
'64 Corvette.                   

09:07.747 --> 09:10.315
          '57 Tee-Bird          
      two weeks ago today.      

09:10.383 --> 09:12.351
    Oh, man.                    

09:12.419 --> 09:15.087
Does it still                   
really hurt inside?             

09:15.155 --> 09:16.989
                  Sometimes more
                    than others.

09:17.057 --> 09:18.991
                  Like, when I'm
                  late for work,

09:19.059 --> 09:21.460
      and I run out of the house
         and try and jump in it.

09:21.528 --> 09:23.996
              Just end up in the
                 gutter weeping.

09:24.064 --> 09:26.131
Oh, man, I hear you,            
I hear you.                     

09:26.199 --> 09:27.199
                         It just
                     isn't fair.

09:27.267 --> 09:28.634
Oh, no kidding.                 

09:28.702 --> 09:31.904
You know, when bad things happen
to good-looking people.         

09:33.640 --> 09:36.642
                  Oh, here's you
                in glee club.   

09:36.710 --> 09:39.378
                  Captain of the
                    debate team.

09:39.446 --> 09:40.579
Mm-hmm.                         
                Oh, Mark, you...

09:40.647 --> 09:42.815
                 Oh, look, Water
                  Polo Champion.

09:42.882 --> 09:44.216
                        Oh.     

09:44.284 --> 09:46.752
                     Head of the
                 prom committee.

09:46.820 --> 09:47.953
    Most likely to succeed.     

09:48.021 --> 09:49.521
            Are you in there,   
                      Miss Howe?

09:49.589 --> 09:50.789
     Well, sure I am. Here.     

09:54.961 --> 09:57.062
    I... I know I am.           

09:57.130 --> 09:58.931
Wait. There.                    
                Oh, yes.        

09:58.998 --> 10:01.133
     Yes, there's my elbow      
        on protest day.         

10:01.201 --> 10:02.468
                             Oh.

10:02.535 --> 10:04.503
                What were you   
                     protesting?

10:04.571 --> 10:05.804
      Oh, I-I don't know.       

10:05.872 --> 10:08.507
    The war, cafeteria food,    
        the bomb.               

10:08.575 --> 10:10.275
 Uh, it's just a real neat way  
         to meet kids.          

10:10.343 --> 10:12.644
         Look at this.          

10:12.712 --> 10:14.346
         18 years old--         

10:14.414 --> 10:16.448
    ready to graduate           
     and take on the world.     

10:16.516 --> 10:17.950
                  Wait a minute.

10:18.018 --> 10:20.319
         You graduated from high
        school when you were 18?

10:20.387 --> 10:22.354
                 What, did Daddy
              pull some strings?

10:27.727 --> 10:28.861
                    (gasps)     

10:28.928 --> 10:30.963
             Look at this! Look,
         look, look, look, look!

10:31.031 --> 10:33.198
        Here's our production   
            of <i>South Pacific.</i>   

10:33.266 --> 10:36.969
     Oh, Mark, you were the most
    powerful Emile de Becque.   

10:37.037 --> 10:38.637
Oh, and you were a great...     

10:38.705 --> 10:41.140
one of the nurses that washed   
Nellie Forbush's hair.          

10:41.207 --> 10:42.975
Hey, Kelly,                     
how's it going back there?      

10:43.043 --> 10:45.844
Oh, fine. I just came out       
      to get myself a soda      

10:45.912 --> 10:47.846
         and some suds          
    for the Philster.           

10:50.950 --> 10:52.685
Kelly, why are you              
doing this?                     

10:52.752 --> 10:54.653
                  I want Woody's
             friends to like me.

10:54.721 --> 10:56.455
Did you buy them                
a round?                        
                            Yes.

10:56.523 --> 10:58.724
You'll never                    
get rid of them.                

11:00.827 --> 11:02.027
                You know, Carla,

11:02.095 --> 11:03.996
             you're the only one
              of Woody's friends

11:04.064 --> 11:05.898
                  that I haven't
            spent time with yet.

11:05.965 --> 11:08.033
                 Let's you and I
            have a chat, hmm?   

11:08.101 --> 11:11.270
I'd better put on               
my thinking cap.                

11:13.139 --> 11:15.007
Oh, doll,                       
I have got to run.              

11:15.075 --> 11:16.175
Kiss, kiss.                     

11:16.242 --> 11:17.343
                    Oh, Mark,   
                        so soon?

11:17.410 --> 11:19.178
      Yeah. Well, I found       
     this great apartment,      

11:19.245 --> 11:22.681
but the rent is sky-high,       
 so I'm interviewing roommates. 

11:22.749 --> 11:24.483
This could be exhausting.       

11:24.551 --> 11:25.784
             Later.             

11:27.087 --> 11:29.688
So that was                     
the old boyfriend, huh?         

11:29.756 --> 11:32.257
(sighing):                      
Yeah. Can you believe it?       

11:32.325 --> 11:35.361
How could I have been           
so stupid?                      

11:35.428 --> 11:37.963
I should have seen it           
way back in high school.        

